<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-738-610  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 738 610.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Wall Street Journal  August 15 1990 pB1(W) pB1(E) 25 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Data security: computer virus poses small risk. (Computers)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hooper, Laurence.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Security experts say that many large corporations have fallenvictim to the hype surrounding computer viruses.andP;  Companies areprotecting against viruses while ignoring other pressing problems.andO;According to one study, 53 percent of corporate computers willhave anti-virus protection by 1991.andP;  However, experts say computerviruses are often mere annoyances and are not real threats,accounting for only 3 percent of data loss.andP;  Genuine threats thatcorporations face include: unauthorized access to information bycompany personnel; careless data input; failure to back-up dataproperly; natural disasters; and power failures or water damage.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer virusesData SecurityData IntegritySecurity SystemsUnited States. National Center for Computer Crime DataComputer Crimes.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Data damage (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>